05811nam a22008175i 9781501764769DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021054779  a97815017647697 a10.1515/97815017647692doi  a(DE-B1597)612438  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBT93b.C645 2022 7aREL0400002bisacsh1 aCohen, Jeremy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Salvation of Israel :bJews in Christian Eschatology from Paul to the Puritans /cJeremy Cohen. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b17 b&w halftones, 8 color halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMedieval Societies, Religions, and Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. All Israel Will Be Saved -- t1. Paul and the Mystery of Israel’s Salvation -- t2. The Pauline Legacy -- t3. The Latin West -- tPart II. The Jews and Antichrist -- t4. Antichrist and the Jews in Early Christianity -- t5. Jews and the Many Faces of Antichrist in the Middle Ages -- t6. Antichrist and Jews in Literature, Drama, and Visual Arts -- tPart III. At the Forefront of the Redemption -- t7. Honorius Augustodunensis, the Song of Songs, and Synagoga Conversa -- t8. Jewish Converts and Christian Salvation -- t9. Puritans, Jews, and the End of Days -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Salvation of Israel investigates Christianity's eschatological Jew, the role and characteristics of the Jews at the end of days in the Christian imagination. It explores the depth of Christian ambivalence regarding these Jews, from Paul's Epistle to the Romans, through late antiquity and the Middle Ages, to the Puritans of the seventeenth century. Jeremy Cohen contends that few aspects of a religion shed as much light on the character and the self-understanding of its adherents as its expectations for the end of time. Moreover, eschatological beliefs express and mold an outlook toward non-believers, situating them in an overall scheme of human history and conditioning interaction with them as that history unfolds.Cohen's close readings of biblical commentary, theological texts, and Christian iconography reveal the dual role of the Jews of the last days. For rejecting belief and salvation in Jesus Christ, they have been linked to the false messiah, the Antichrist, the agent of Satan and the exemplary embodiment of evil. Yet from its inception, Christianity has also hinged its hopes for the Second Coming on the enlightenment and repentance of the Jews; for then, as Paul prophesized, "all Israel will be saved."In its vast historical scope, from the ancient Mediterranean world of early Christianity to seventeenth century England and New England, The Salvation of Israel offers a nuanced and insightful assessment of Christian attitudes toward Jews, rife with inconsistency and complexity, thus contributing significantly to our understanding of Jewish-Christian relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aAntichristxHistory of doctrines. 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaism. 0aEnd of the worldxHistory of doctrines. 0aJudaism (Christian theology)xHistory of doctrines. 0aJudaismxRelationsxChristianity. 4aJewish Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  ajudeo-centrism, christian eschatology, jews and Christianity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz9783110